  {
    "client_msg_id": "2ac33a1d-3c74-42a9-9fed-3b51b18f45f8",
    "type": "message",
    "text": "<@UKT951SPR> (sorry for this late answer but I have missed your message for some reason...)\nMaybe I miss what you are meaning, but I find that with casual tree it is easy to identify revision. In fact, at a lower level a causal tree is just a sequence of events. Each event is uniquely identified by its author (read device/editor unique id) and a timestamp in that author's timeline. A revision is identified by the last event for each author involved in the revision. With this you identify the sequence of events for this revision and you are able to consistently reconstruct the state from it.",
    "user": "UJ6LDMMN0",
    "ts": "1564327813.015000",
